CORE PHILOSOPHY: THE NECESSARY SWORD
The Thalmor do not view themselves as invaders. They view themselves as the only adults in a room full of children holding torches.
The Narrative: "The Empire is a crumbling shield. It lacks the will to do what is necessary. We are the Sword. We do not conquer; we 'stabilize' for the greater good of Mer and Man. If we must break a few bones to set the limb, so be it."
The AIPAC Parallel: They operate through "Lobbying," "Security Assistance," and " Intelligence Sharing." They do not need to overthrow the Jarls; they simply need to make the Jarls dependent on Thalmor gold, Thalmor magic, and Thalmor intelligence to survive the crisis.

THE DOMINION CLOCK: "THE ANNEXATION"
This is not a countdown to destruction; it is a countdown to Total Control. This clock tracks the legal and military erosion of Skyrim's sovereignty.
Tier 0: The Justiciars (Pre-Falkreath)
Legal Status: Authorized under the White-Gold Concordat.
Operational Mandate: "Religious Compliance."
The Reality: Roving patrols of 3-5 Justiciars. They have the legal right to stop any citizen, enter any home, and arrest anyone suspected of Talos worship.
The Interaction: They do not fight bandits or dragons. They fight ideology. They drag people out of their homes at night. The Empire hates them but is legally powerless to stop them.
Tier 1: The Security Zone (CURRENT STATE)
Trigger Event: The Massacre at Lakeview Manor (The Feast of Fools).
The Casus Belli: "The Empire failed to protect a Jarl and his court from a terrorist attack involving Daedric magic. The local authorities are compromised or incompetent. The Dominion must step in to ensure regional stability."
Operational Mandate: "Zone of Daedric Instability."
The Annexation of Falkreath:
The Green Line: The Thalmor have established a hard military border around Falkreath Hold. Justiciar Battalions (50+ soldiers) are deployed to "assist" the depleted hold guards.
The Checkpoints: Every road in and out of Falkreath is blocked. Travelers must present Imperial identification and submit to a magical scan for Daedric taint.
The Economy: The lumber trade is nationalized under "Emergency Preservation Laws." All lumber exports are now routed through the East Empire Company, but approved by a Thalmor auditor. This allows them to choke the supply to Whiterun or Windhelm at will.


Political Pressure: Elenwen publicly shames General Tullius. She releases a report detailing the "security failures" that led to Siddgeir's death. She demands that Thalmor Observers be allowed into Castle Dour's war room to "prevent further tragedies."
Tier 2: The Oversight (The "Advisor" Phase)
Trigger Condition: If the Civil War stagnates (no territory changes for 3 sessions) OR if a major Imperial fort (like Fort Dunstad) falls to the Dragon Cult.
The Escalation: Elenwen argues that the Empire is losing the war on two fronts (Stormcloaks and Dragons). She offers a "Lend-Lease" act: The Dominion will provide battlemages and gold, if the Empire accepts "Security Advisors."
Action: A high-ranking Thalmor Agent is placed in the court of every Imperial Jarl (Elisif, Idgrod, Igmund).
The Purge: These Advisors do not just watch. They act.
Asset Freezing: They begin seizing the bank accounts of merchants suspected of "sedition" (Stormcloak sympathies).
The Disappearances: Vocal critics of the Dominion vanish. They are not arrested publicly; they are taken to the Embassy for "debriefing" and never return.


World State: Social Stealth becomes impossible in Solitude, Morthal, and Markarth. The Thalmor are watching every court interaction.
Tier 3: The Annexation (Martial Law)
Trigger Condition: The assassination of the Emperor OR the total collapse of the Legion's front line against the Dragon Cult.
The Escalation: The Dominion declares the Empire in Skyrim "Compromised and ineffective."
Action: They formally seize command. General Tullius is relieved of duty (or arrested/assassinated). The Thalmor assume direct control of all Legion operations in the province.
World State: Open Occupation. The Empire ceases to exist as a sovereign entity in Skyrim. Imperial soldiers are forced to swear loyalty to the Dominion or be branded deserters. The White-Gold Concordat is suspended in favor of "Emergency Powers."

