OCCUPATION MECHANICS: THE TOOLS OF CONTROL
The Thalmor do not just use swords; they use bureaucracy and economics as weapons.
1. Asset Forfeiture (Economic Warfare)
When a Hold enters Tier 1 (Security Zone), the Thalmor enact "Civil Forfeiture" laws.
The Logic: "To prevent funding of terrorism, all assets of suspected insurgents are placed in protective custody."
Game Effect:
Shortage of High-Tier Gear: Local smiths and enchanters are stripped of their best inventory (Ebony, Glass, Grand Soul Gems). These items are moved to the Thalmor Evidence Locker (usually inside the local Embassy or Jarl's Longhouse).
Player Impact: Players cannot buy High-Tier items in occupied holds. They must steal them back from the Justiciars.
The Black Market: Prices for illegal goods (weapons, potions) in the Thieves Guild or fences triple (+300%).


2. The Travel Permit System (The Blacklist)
When a Hold enters Tier 1, freedom of movement ends.
The Logic: "To track insurgent movements."
Game Effect:
Checkpoints: Major roads are blocked by barricades manned by Justiciars.
The Papers: Travelers must possess a "Stamped Imperial writ of Passage."
The Blacklist: Specific NPCs (contacts, trainers, quest givers) are placed on a "No Travel" list. If the party needs to move an NPC (like a witness or an expert), they cannot just walk out the gate. They must smuggle them out.


3. The Informant Network
The Thalmor pay well for information.
Game Effect: In an occupied hold, any Social Failure (Guile check) with a random NPC has a 25% chance of resulting in that NPC reporting the party to the Thalmor for a reward.
Atmosphere: Paranoia. No one speaks openly in taverns anymore. The Bards stop singing political songs.

